args: My sister changed once she died.\nShe's been keeping all the villagers trapped here,\nforcing us to repeat that day over and over.
The only thing worse than seeing her so\nmiserable was knowing that I couldn't help her.\nBut there was a glimmer of hope.
Someone from the outside found\ntheir way in again?
If my sister finds her, she'll make sure\nthis lady shares our fate.
Wait... But she's protectedâ€”by some\npowerful force. Maybe it's enough to\nkeep my sister from noticing...
Easy with the mitts, babe.\nI'm a...feather duster kinda guy...\nZzzzz...zing...
It talked?! No way. That lady's not\nnormal if she's got something like this.
Maybe... Maybe she can help us.
So you figured Cassandra here was your\nbest shot at de-ghasting your sister, huh?
But you couldn't let the little psycho catch\nwind of that plan, so you hid me in that\ndrawer. Sure. Fine. I get it.

But tearing my body to shreds just so
you can leave the old bag a HINT?!
You're worse than a greasy-fingered
toddler manhandling a picture book!
Oh, grow up, Douleur.\nShe was desperate.

Then you were the one watching me
as I inspected the barrier surrounding
this village. And when the old woman 
was harping on me about having a drink...
I snuck around behind so nobody would\nsee me and shoved my sister into you.
You're my little heroine, you know that?\nI promise to fix all this. Sorceress's honor.
Let's back it up a second here. What's\nshe so torqued about in the first place?
I always thought she got this way\nbecause she was so sad about dying...
I've been through this over and over,\nwaiting to hear his answer.
Is your sister's friend trapped here\nin this world with you? The boy.
Did you notice anything different between\nthe two of them, leading up to the festival?
...I see. Thank you. That solves the mystery\nof what's spurring her to gruesome action.
Yes. It's a sentiment I know well.\nPainfully so, even.
I'm going to go talk to her.\nYou two stay here.
She should be at the riverside. I'll teach\nyou a way to get there without being seen.
Thank you, dearie. And don't worry.\nI promise I'll help your sister.
You come willingly to the slaughter?\nHee hee. What a foolish woman.
It hurts to look at you. To see you clinging\nso desperately to such a fragile possibility.
You've thrown all logic out the window,\nthe perceptions of others be damned.\n...It's like gazing into a mirror.
Don't talk as if you understand.\nWhat could you possibly know about me?
You told him how you feel. Your friend.\nYou confessed your love to him before\nthe festival.
And he said he'd give you his reply today.
It's the curse of being a genius sorceress,\ndearie. I see everything.
So you broke your little sister's heart and\nmade plans to meet with him instead.
But he never arrived. Then the flash\nflood came, and your time was up.
Still, you needed to hear his reply.\nAnd so you repeated that fateful day,\nagain and again. But in the end...
This time will be different!\nThis time, for sure, he'llâ€”
He didn't come to the festival at all\nthat day. He wasn't caught in the flood.\nHe isn't among the dead here, dearie.
But I suspect you knew that from the start.\nThat he yet walks upon the earth.

You couldn't face that truth.
Couldn't bear to accept it.
Even if it meant damning an entire
village to suffer alongside you.
Then what was I supposed to do?!
Even if he turned me down, there would\nalways be another chance so long as I\nlived to see another day. But now...
There's nothing leftâ€”not even the faintest\nglimmer of hope! Sadness is an abyss,\nand it has swallowed me whole!
I'm not so callous as to say ï¼‚get over him.ï¼‚\nBut think about what you're clinging to.
Think of what he would say if he saw you\nnow. Would he love what you've become?
What I've become... Ha ha, who could\nlove this? My soul's stained dark as pitch.
But it need not get any darker.
In truth, I'm in no position to lecture.\nYou and I are one and the same.
Once little miss psycho returned to the\nsource of mana, we made it out. Looks\nlike the other souls were freed, too.
Thank you, nice witch. And Mr. Douleur\nand the other guy, too.
Heh. My pleasure, dearie.\nBut who do you mean by ï¼‚other guyï¼‚?
The one who was protecting you.\nHe was strong as a dragon!
I should be going, too.\nBye bye, and thanks again!
She's returned to mana now, too.
That's our cue, Douleur.\nThe comfort of home awaits.
There's just one thing bugging me, Cass.
Why were you wearing that yukata\nin their memories?
Maybe it was because of this.\nI had it stashed in my pocket.
It's one of the ingredients I need to bring\nthat old fool back. It houses his mana.

Perhaps that selfsame mana manifested
as the yukata I woreâ€”to keep me safe.
Heh... Makes for a pleasant daydream,
if nothing else.
Yeah, real romantic for a gal your age.\n...Huh? Somebody's coming this way.
Well, this is quite the chance encounter.\nDid you come from the old abandoned\nvillage, miss?
Something like that.\nDo you have business there?
Just paying my respects. An old friend of\nmine sleeps thereâ€”one I made a promise\nto a long, long time ago...

It was about four decades ago. Work had
taken me to the next village over, and I
was hurrying home to meet my friend, but
the roads were closed due to heavy rain.

Getting stranded like that wound up
saving my life, but she wasn't so lucky.
I lost her without ever getting the chance
to tell her something important.
So I come back every year to offer a\nprayer and repeat my answer to her. I can\nonly hope it reaches her up in heaven.
...Bah, what am I droning on about?\nI'm sure you've no interest in hearing\nan old man's regrets.
You might be surprised, dearie. And I'm\nsure she hears you loud and clear.
Here. You can give this flower to her,\nif you like.
Is that a hibiscus? That's mighty kind of\nyou. You don't mind letting me have it?
It's yours. I've come to realize\nit doesn't take a flower for one's\nfeelings to bear fruit.
